‚òÅÔ∏è AWS EFS (Elastic File System) ‚Äì Notes
1Ô∏è‚É£ EFS

Amazon EFS is a fully managed, scalable file storage service for EC2.
It provides a shared file system that multiple instances can access at the same time.

2Ô∏è‚É£ File System Type

EFS uses the NFS (Network File System) protocol.
It is commonly used for Linux-based workloads that need shared access.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Scalability

EFS automatically scales storage up and down as files are added or removed.
There is no need to manually provision storage size.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Performance Modes

EFS offers different performance modes like General Purpose and Max I/O.
These modes help optimize latency or throughput based on application needs.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Throughput Modes

EFS provides Bursting Throughput and Provisioned Throughput.
This controls how fast data can be read or written.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Availability & Durability

EFS stores data across multiple Availability Zones.
This ensures high availability and durability of data.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Security

EFS supports encryption at rest and in transit.
Access is controlled using security groups and IAM policies.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Access Points

EFS Access Points simplify access management for applications.
They provide application-specific entry points with defined permissions.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Use Cases

EFS is used for shared web servers, content management systems, and home directories.
It is ideal when multiple EC2 instances need the same data.

üîü EFS vs EBS (Quick Idea)

EFS is shared and scalable file storage, while EBS is attached to a single EC2.
EFS supports multiple EC2 instances at the same time.
